---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "What is the cheapest GCP Compute Engine machine type for general workloads?",
    answer: "E2 machine types are generally the most cost-effective for general-purpose workloads. An e2-standard-2 (2 vCPUs, 8 GB RAM) costs approximately $0.067/hour on-demand in us-central1. For even lower costs, consider E2 Spot VMs which can be up to 91% cheaper, though they may be preempted with 30 seconds notice."
  },
  {
    question: "How do Committed Use Discounts (CUDs) work on GCP?",
    answer: "Committed Use Discounts require you to commit to a minimum level of resources (vCPUs and memory) for either 1 year or 3 years in exchange for discounted prices. 1-year CUDs offer approximately 37% off on-demand pricing, while 3-year CUDs offer up to 55% off. CUDs are flexible — they apply automatically to any matching VM in the same region, not tied to specific instances."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the difference between Preemptible VMs and Spot VMs on GCP?",
    answer: "Spot VMs are the successor to Preemptible VMs on GCP. Both offer deeply discounted compute (up to 91% off) in exchange for the possibility of being interrupted. The key difference is that Preemptible VMs had a maximum runtime of 24 hours, while Spot VMs have no maximum runtime limit. However, both can be reclaimed by Google with 30 seconds notice when capacity is needed elsewhere."
  },
  {
    question: "Does GCP offer automatic discounts without any commitment?",
    answer: "Yes — Sustained Use Discounts (SUDs) are applied automatically when you run N1, N2, or N2D machine types for a significant portion of the billing month. The discount scales up to 30% for instances running the full month. No sign-up or commitment is required; GCP calculates SUDs automatically based on usage. Note that E2, T2D, and C2 machine types do not qualify for SUDs."
  },
  {
    question: "How is Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE) priced?",
    answer: "GKE charges $0.10/hour per cluster for cluster management (Autopilot or Standard mode with 1+ nodes), which is approximately $73/month. However, one Zonal cluster per billing account is free. Node VMs are billed at standard Compute Engine rates. GKE Autopilot pricing is based on pod resource requests (vCPU, memory, storage) rather than node capacity, which can be more efficient for variable workloads."
  },
  {
    question: "When should I choose Cloud Run over Compute Engine?",
    answer: "Cloud Run is ideal for stateless HTTP workloads with variable or unpredictable traffic. You pay only for the CPU and memory consumed during request processing (minimum 100ms billing). At low traffic, Cloud Run can scale to zero and cost nothing. Compute Engine is better for stateful applications, long-running background jobs, custom OS requirements, or workloads that run consistently at high utilization where a committed VM would be cheaper."
  }
];
---
<BaseLayout
  title="GCP Pricing Calculator — Google Cloud Compute Pricing Guide"
  description="Complete GCP pricing guide covering Compute Engine machine types (N2, E2, C2, T2D), on-demand vs preemptible vs Spot VMs, Committed Use Discounts, Sustained Use Discounts, GKE, and Cloud Run pricing."
  tool="gcp-pricing-calculator"
  faq={faq}
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">GCP Pricing Calculator</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Google Cloud Compute Engine machine types, pricing models, discounts, and cost-optimization strategies — all in one place.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Machine type comparison</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Committed Use Discounts guide</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Spot VM & preemptible pricing</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> GKE & Cloud Run breakdown</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">GCP Compute Engine Machine Families</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    Google Cloud organizes Compute Engine into distinct machine families, each optimized for different workload profiles. Choosing the right family is the single biggest lever for cost optimization — differences of 30–50% in hourly rate are common between families for equivalent resource counts.
  </p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    <strong>E2 (Economy):</strong> Best price-performance for general workloads. Uses a shared-core model with dynamic resource allocation. No Sustained Use Discounts, but very low baseline cost. Great for web servers, small databases, and development environments.
  </p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    <strong>N2 / N2D (General Purpose):</strong> Balanced performance for a broad range of workloads. N2 uses Intel Cascade Lake processors, N2D uses AMD EPYC. Both support Sustained Use Discounts and Committed Use Discounts. Recommended for production workloads needing consistent performance.
  </p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    <strong>C2 / C2D (Compute-Optimized):</strong> Highest per-core performance on GCP. Ideal for gaming, HPC, ad serving, and CPU-intensive analytics. Higher hourly cost but fewer cores needed for the same throughput. C2D (AMD) offers slightly better price-performance than C2 (Intel) for vectorized workloads.
  </p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
    <strong>T2D (Scale-Out):</strong> AMD EPYC Milan processors with excellent single-threaded performance and competitive pricing. Best for scale-out workloads like web serving, containerized microservices, and media transcoding.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Common Machine Type Pricing (us-central1, on-demand)</h2>
  <table class="w-full text-sm text-text-muted mb-6 border-collapse">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Machine Type</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">vCPUs</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Memory</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">On-Demand/hr</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">1-yr CUD/hr</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Spot/hr (est.)</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">e2-standard-2</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">2</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">8 GB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.0670</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.0420</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">~$0.0067</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">e2-standard-4</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">4</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">16 GB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.1340</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.0841</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">~$0.0134</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">n2-standard-4</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">4</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">16 GB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.1942</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.1217</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">~$0.0194</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">n2-standard-8</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">8</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">32 GB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.3884</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.2434</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">~$0.0388</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">c2-standard-8</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">8</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">32 GB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.4170</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.2627</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">~$0.0417</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">t2d-standard-4</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">4</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">16 GB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.1712</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.1075</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">~$0.0171</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mb-6">Prices are approximate and subject to change. Always verify current pricing at <strong>cloud.google.com/compute/all-pricing</strong>. Spot VM prices fluctuate based on regional capacity.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Pricing Models: On-Demand, Spot, and Committed Use</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    GCP offers multiple pricing models that can dramatically reduce your compute bill. Understanding when to use each is the key to cloud cost optimization.
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-text-muted mb-4 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>On-Demand:</strong> Full price, no commitment. Best for unpredictable workloads, new projects, or short-term needs. No upfront payment.</li>
    <li><strong>Spot VMs:</strong> Up to 91% discount vs on-demand. VMs can be preempted with 30 seconds notice. Ideal for batch jobs, CI/CD pipelines, data processing, and fault-tolerant workloads.</li>
    <li><strong>Committed Use Discounts (1-year):</strong> ~37% off on-demand. No upfront payment required. Best for stable production workloads running 24/7.</li>
    <li><strong>Committed Use Discounts (3-year):</strong> Up to 55% off on-demand. Requires a 3-year commitment on resource spend in a region. Maximum savings for long-term infrastructure.</li>
    <li><strong>Sustained Use Discounts (automatic):</strong> Applied automatically for N1/N2/N2D VMs running 25%+ of the month. Scales up to 30% for full-month usage. No action required.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">GKE Pricing Breakdown</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    Google Kubernetes Engine has a straightforward pricing model: you pay for the cluster management fee plus the underlying Compute Engine nodes.
  </p>
  <table class="w-full text-sm text-text-muted mb-6 border-collapse">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">GKE Component</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Pricing</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Notes</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Cluster management fee</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.10/hour (~$73/mo)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Per cluster; one free zonal cluster per account</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Worker nodes</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Standard Compute Engine rates</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">All discounts (CUD, Spot, SUD) apply</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Autopilot pods</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.0445/vCPU-hr + $0.0049/GB-hr</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Billed per pod resource request, not node</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Persistent disk</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.04/GB-mo (standard) / $0.17/GB-mo (SSD)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">PersistentVolumeClaims billed separately</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Cloud Run Pricing</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    Cloud Run is GCP's fully managed serverless container platform. You pay only for what you use — there is no charge when your service is not handling requests.
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-text-muted mb-4 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>CPU:</strong> $0.00002400/vCPU-second (billed only during request processing)</li>
    <li><strong>Memory:</strong> $0.00000250/GB-second</li>
    <li><strong>Requests:</strong> $0.40 per million requests</li>
    <li><strong>Free tier:</strong> 2 million requests/month, 360,000 vCPU-seconds, 180,000 GB-seconds — enough for many small services at zero cost</li>
    <li><strong>CPU always-on option:</strong> CPU is allocated for the full instance lifetime (even between requests), allowing background work. Priced at a slight premium but with always-allocated CPU charges.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
    For a service handling 10 million requests/month, each taking 200ms with 1 vCPU and 256 MB RAM, the estimated Cloud Run cost is approximately $80–100/month — often significantly cheaper than a dedicated VM that sits idle between traffic spikes.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Cost Optimization Strategies</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-text-muted mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>Right-size before committing:</strong> Use Cloud Monitoring to identify underutilized VMs and right-size them before purchasing CUDs.</li>
    <li><strong>Mix Spot and on-demand:</strong> Use managed instance groups with a mix of Spot VMs (80%) and on-demand (20%) for fault-tolerant workloads to save 70%+.</li>
    <li><strong>Use regional commitments:</strong> CUDs apply to any matching VM in a region — you can upgrade, downgrade, or change machine types without losing the discount.</li>
    <li><strong>Enable SUD automatically:</strong> N2 and N2D machines accrue Sustained Use Discounts automatically. No configuration needed — just avoid restarting VMs mid-month unnecessarily.</li>
    <li><strong>Consider Cloud Run for APIs:</strong> Variable-traffic APIs and microservices are almost always cheaper on Cloud Run than on always-on VMs at moderate request volumes.</li>
    <li><strong>Use committed use for GKE nodes:</strong> GKE node pools run on Compute Engine — all VM discounts apply. Apply CUDs to the node machine types for maximum savings.</li>
  </ul>

  <AdUnit slot="auto" format="auto" label="Advertisement" />
  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
  <ToolPageCta currentTool="gcp-pricing-calculator" relatedTags={['gcp', 'google-cloud', 'cloud', 'pricing', 'cost-optimization', 'devops']} />
</BaseLayout>
